291
00:19:53,024 --> 00:19:55,686
You have got a lot of nerve judging me.

292
00:19:56,361 --> 00:20:00,593
You have had a roof over your head,
three meals a day, private schools.

293
00:20:00,699 --> 00:20:02,496
The reason you even know how to write...

294
00:20:02,601 --> 00:20:05,593
is because of this abhorrent corporate job
that I have.

295
00:20:06,071 --> 00:20:10,337
I am not about to apologize to you
for who I am. Do you understand me?

296
00:20:11,276 --> 00:20:13,244
You don't understand me.

297
00:20:13,645 --> 00:20:16,546
I found something I'm passionate about, Ma.

298
00:20:16,815 --> 00:20:19,579
And I'm not going back to school, period.

299
00:20:19,918 --> 00:20:23,649
All right? I don't like it, I don't fit in there,
it just ain't happening.

300
00:20:23,755 --> 00:20:25,382
You don't fit in.

301
00:20:28,526 --> 00:20:29,754
I get it.

302
00:20:30,228 --> 00:20:34,187
Are we have a little black-girl pity party?
Is that what this is?

303
00:20:34,466 --> 00:20:38,095
I don't fit in at NYU
because I'm little Miss Street Gangster?

304
00:20:38,203 --> 00:20:41,900
Is that what this is?
No, let me tell you something, homeslice.

305
00:20:42,007 --> 00:20:46,603
You are a bourgeois nigger from Montclair,
New Jersey, just like your mama.

306
00:20:46,711 --> 00:20:48,542
- What did you say?
- You heard me.

307
00:20:48,647 --> 00:20:50,774
- I'm a nigger?
- That's right.

308
00:20:50,882 --> 00:20:55,046
I can't believe this. You're tripping.
So what are you, Mom? Are you a nigger?

309
00:20:55,153 --> 00:20:56,643
You're damn skippy I'm a nigger.

310
00:20:56,755 --> 00:20:59,383
- Which one, a house nigger?
- No.

311
00:20:59,491 --> 00:21:02,187
I'm a field nigger, 'cause I go to work.

312
00:21:02,293 --> 00:21:04,158
- For real?
- Yes.

313
00:21:04,629 --> 00:21:07,120
And I am out in the field right now.

314
00:21:07,232 --> 00:21:08,631
And you gonna shuffle?

315
00:21:08,733 --> 00:21:11,429
I'm gonna pick some cotton right here.

316
00:21:12,971 --> 00:21:14,438
That's right.

317
00:21:15,674 --> 00:21:17,039
That's right.

318
00:21:18,610 --> 00:21:20,339
I can't believe you.

319
00:21:51,109 --> 00:21:52,201
Shit.

320
00:22:09,861 --> 00:22:10,828
Shit.

321
00:22:23,708 --> 00:22:25,835
Okay, the ball's in your court now.

322
00:22:25,944 --> 00:22:29,311
Your foster mom's not gonna
beg you to do this. You know that.

323
00:22:29,414 --> 00:22:31,541
But it would make her very happy.

324
00:22:31,649 --> 00:22:34,914
You can't deny her that
because you're afraid to pick up the phone...

325
00:22:35,019 --> 00:22:37,351
- and call this guy...
- I ain't afraid of nothing.

326
00:22:37,455 --> 00:22:39,753
You don't know nothing about me.

327
00:22:40,759 --> 00:22:45,093
- I'm trying to help you, Samel.
- I don't remember asking for your help.

328
00:22:47,732 --> 00:22:49,131
I got to go.

329
00:23:05,884 --> 00:23:07,374
So, Arianna couldn't make it?

330
00:23:07,485 --> 00:23:10,420
She had a little fire she had to put out
back at the office...

331
00:23:10,522 --> 00:23:11,955
but she sends her regrets.

332
00:23:12,056 --> 00:23:16,288
- Have you worked for her long?
- No, actually she took over about a year ago.

333
00:23:16,594 --> 00:23:18,824
- Great lady.
- Yeah, smart lady.

334
00:23:20,131 --> 00:23:22,622
This place is so funny. Pickles.

335
00:23:23,802 --> 00:23:26,771
I used to come here with my mother
when I was a kid.

336
00:23:26,871 --> 00:23:29,066
I had my first egg cream here.

337
00:23:30,408 --> 00:23:32,774
We're signing the deal on this place today.

338
00:23:32,877 --> 00:23:34,367
- You're kidding.
- No.

339
00:23:34,479 --> 00:23:36,970
And by the time you guys move in
across the street...

340
00:23:37,081 --> 00:23:40,346
you'll have a high-rise
full of potential customers right here.

341
00:23:40,451 --> 00:23:42,180
That's fantastic, Ron.

342
00:23:42,287 --> 00:23:44,812
It is. We've got a Hard Rock Cafe coming in.

343
00:23:44,923 --> 00:23:47,323
And you know the Brooklyn Diner
in midtown Manhattan?

344
00:23:47,425 --> 00:23:50,189
They're gonna open a place here.
Authentic diner food.

345
00:23:50,295 --> 00:23:52,286
This neighborhood is about to explode.

346
00:23:52,397 --> 00:23:57,061
You will certainly be able to get a milkshake
without any difficulty around here.

347
00:23:59,237 --> 00:24:03,196
Seriously, though,
I think this is gonna be great for our people.

348
00:24:03,308 --> 00:24:05,902
Stores of quality in our neighborhood
for a change.

349
00:24:06,010 --> 00:24:07,102
Right.

350
00:24:07,212 --> 00:24:09,874
I mean, it can definitely be a challenge, too.

351
00:24:09,981 --> 00:24:12,973
I work with the Harlem Store
and it's a similar situation.

352
00:24:13,084 --> 00:24:15,951
I mean, Banana Republic
is an upscale store...

353
00:24:16,054 --> 00:24:18,022
but it is a store for everybody.

354
00:24:18,122 --> 00:24:20,191
I mean, us black folks
make money, too, right?

355
00:24:20,191 --> 00:24:20,486
I mean, us black folks
make money, too, right?

356
00:24:20,592 --> 00:24:22,822
We don't discriminate.
We want everybody's money.

357
00:24:22,927 --> 00:24:24,622
Absolutely. Exactly.

358
00:24:24,729 --> 00:24:27,357
And it is a big change,
I mean, given what's here now.

359
00:24:27,465 --> 00:24:29,763
That's part of what's so exciting about it.

360
00:24:29,868 --> 00:24:32,359
Out with the old and in with the new, right?

361
00:24:32,470 --> 00:24:34,529
- Your drinks.
- Thank you.

362
00:24:34,639 --> 00:24:38,973
- So, Morgan Ventura has this whole area.
- Three square blocks, for now.

363
00:24:39,377 --> 00:24:41,868
What is the residential part
of the project like?

364
00:24:41,980 --> 00:24:43,413
It's all condos.

365
00:24:43,514 --> 00:24:46,074
Yeah, we didn't have to do
the affordable housing thing.

366
00:24:46,184 --> 00:24:49,551
- Really?
- Yeah, I think the politicians understand...

367
00:24:49,654 --> 00:24:52,088
that you can't make the thing work
if you're forced...

368
00:24:52,190 --> 00:24:54,658
to stick some project
smack down in the middle of it.

369
00:24:54,759 --> 00:24:56,021
The people from the PJ's...

370
00:24:56,127 --> 00:24:59,722
ain't gonna be spending their benjamins
at Banana Republic, right?

371
00:25:00,531 --> 00:25:02,761
I'm being crude, but seriously.

372
00:25:02,867 --> 00:25:06,325
I think in general people are happy
that we're coming in here.

373
00:25:06,437 --> 00:25:08,166
The longtime neighborhood residents...

374
00:25:08,273 --> 00:25:12,107
are tired of hearing gunshots
and seeing graffiti everywhere they look.

375
00:25:12,210 --> 00:25:15,270
- They welcome change.
- True. That is true.

376
00:25:15,380 --> 00:25:17,678
- Hi, guys.
- Arianna.

377
00:25:17,782 --> 00:25:21,149
Arianna, it's great to see you.
I thought you couldn't make it.

378
00:25:21,252 --> 00:25:23,345
- No, I wanted to but...
- Here, have a seat.

379
00:25:23,454 --> 00:25:25,547
Thank you. Hi, darling.

380
00:25:25,657 --> 00:25:28,125
I was just gonna call in,
but my 12:00 cancelled...

381
00:25:28,226 --> 00:25:30,387
so I thought I'd just come join you guys.

382
00:25:30,495 --> 00:25:32,087
I'm glad you did.

383
00:25:32,764 --> 00:25:34,959
I have a few questions now that you're here.

384
00:25:35,066 --> 00:25:37,500
- How far have you gotten?
- We just...

385
00:25:37,602 --> 00:25:39,695
We haven't even started, really.

386
00:25:39,804 --> 00:25:43,137
What I wanted to ask you about
was the renegotiation on the terms.

387
00:25:43,241 --> 00:25:45,903
Okay, right now
they're set at 10, 20, and 30 years.

388
00:25:46,010 --> 00:25:50,845
Ron, I don't know if we feel comfortable
renegotiating after 10 years.

389
00:25:51,149 --> 00:25:55,210
It's probably gonna be three to five years
before this place turns over...

390
00:25:55,320 --> 00:25:57,788
so it's something we could think about.

391
00:25:57,889 --> 00:25:59,686
That's what I was thinking.

392
00:25:59,791 --> 00:26:01,952
Also, in terms of the plans for the facade...

393
00:26:02,060 --> 00:26:04,688
We've already had a sidebar
with the architects about that.

394
00:26:04,796 --> 00:26:07,788
Excellent, okay,
I'll catch up with my office on that later on.

395
00:26:07,899 --> 00:26:10,527
You know, I'm really glad
this thing is happening.

396
00:26:10,635 --> 00:26:11,829
Excuse me, folks.

397
00:26:11,936 --> 00:26:15,064
I have got some work back at the office
that I need to get done.

398
00:26:15,173 --> 00:26:18,142
It looks like everything is cool here
so I am gonna take off.

399
00:26:18,242 --> 00:26:19,368
No, wait a minute.

400
00:26:19,477 --> 00:26:21,707
No, I'm gonna step away now
so I don't distract you.

401
00:26:21,813 --> 00:26:24,577
- You're not a distraction.
- It's okay with me.

402
00:26:25,183 --> 00:26:27,845
Okay. Are you sure?

403
00:26:33,624 --> 00:26:36,024
Is there any way I can get a copy
of a mockup...

404
00:26:36,127 --> 00:26:38,288
of what you discussed with your architects?

405
00:26:40,631 --> 00:26:42,929
...and remember to always smile.

406
00:26:43,034 --> 00:26:44,968
It won't mess up your hair.

